Acting Ipswich mayor Paul Tully, who for years served as deputy to embattled former mayor Paul Pisasale, has topped the first major poll held in the city ahead of the August 19 byelection. Cr Tully received 34.1 per cent of the 933 voters surveyed via telephone on August 3 in the ReachTEL poll, while his fellow councillor Andrew Antoniolli received 27.5 per cent.Photo: Chris Hyde The results showed that the scandals surrounding Mr Pisasale, , has not rubbed off on his former council colleagues, with more than half of respondents seemingly happy to have a sitting councillor take the mayoralty. Policy announcements and preference arrangements will influence the final outcome. The byelection, brought about by Mr Pisasale's resignation in June, will be an optional preferential poll. The poll was conducted by Ipswich branch of the Queensland Community Alliance, which has solidified from a number of church and union organisations in Ipswich, Logan and Brisbane over the past two years.
The alliance is asking for a "new culture of working" for Ipswich in the post-Pisasale era. The ReachTEL poll shows:
